Introduction¶

The gravity data used here is extracted from Budiman (1991) thesis "Interpretation of gravity data over central Jawa [sic], Indonesia". This data consists of 2811 complete Bouguer anomaly data collected during ground surveys in Central Java between 1965 to 1977, reduced using a Bouguer and terrain density of $2670\;\dfrac{kg}{m^3}$ from the observed gravity acceleration values. Gravity data X (Easting, in metres) and Y (Northing, in metres) positions are originally given in the local "Batavia TM 109 SE" coordinate system, whose .wkt file are included in here and read using pyproj.CRS.from_wkt function. Gravity data elevation is sampled from BATNAS' 200 m resolution DEM and bathymetry (using QGIS' Raster analysis>Sample raster values), so they are relative to the mean local sea level/geoid.

We cannot locate any explanation on this gravity data positioning techniques in the literature, so the gravity anomaly uncertainty cannot be estimated with any degree of certainty. Due to the absence of a reliable uncertainty estimate, the central Java gravity anomaly data presented here is not good for scientific publication but is good enough for experimenting with equivalent surface gridding technique as described in Dampney (1969).

So let's start!

Transform The X and Y Coordinates to SRGI UTM Zone 49S¶

We now transform the Easting (X) and Northing (Y) of the local "Batavia TM 109 SE" coordinate system to the current SRGI UTM Zone 49S Easting (X) and Northing (Y). Both the Easting and Northing in the local "Batavia TM 109 SE" and SRGI UTM Zone 49S coordinate systems are in metres. This is to facilitate plotting in modern GIS softwares (like ArcGIS Pro and QGIS) and modules (like cartopy and pygmt).

What is the $\mathbf{A}$ matrix?¶

Assume a three dimensional, orthogonal $x,y,z$ coordinate system with positive $x$ to the right/east, positive $y$ to the front/north, and positive $z$ to the above/up. Given an array of $N$ masses $\mathbf{m} = \left[m_1, m_2, m_3, \dots, m_N\right]$ in this space, the gravity at a point $P\left(x,y,z\right)$ due to these masses is (Roy, 1962; Dampney, 1969)

$$g_P = \sum_{j=0}^{N}{a_{j}m_{j}} \tag{1}$$

with

$$a_j = \frac{K\times\left(z-h_{j}\right)}{\left\{\left(x-\alpha_{j}\right)^{2} + \left(y-\beta_{j}\right)^{2} + \left(z-h_{j}\right)^{2}\right\}^{3/2}}. \tag{2}$$

The original Dampney (1969) formulation puts $\left(h - z_{i}\right)$ since his coordinate system defines the positive $z$ axis downward/below.

The position of the i-th mass is given by $\left(\alpha_{j}, \beta_{j}, h_{j}\right)$ in three dimension. The array grid_mass_centres contains $\alpha_{j}, \beta_{j},$ and $h_{j}$ in the first, second, and third columns consecutively. Assuming all masses are laid on a flat plane at elevation $h$ (as grid_mass_centres does), then $h_{j} = h$ for all points and $a_{j}$ becomes

$$a_j = \frac{K\times\left(z-h\right)}{\left\{\left(x-\alpha_{j}\right)^{2} + \left(y-\beta_{j}\right)^{2} + \left(z-h\right)^{2}\right\}^{3/2}}. \tag{3}$$

If there are $K$ gravity values, $\mathbf{g} = \left[g_1, g_2, g_3, \dots, g_K\right]$, each located on $P_1\left(x_1, y_1, z_1\right), P_2\left(x_2, y_2, z_2\right), \dots, P_K\left(x_K, y_K, z_K\right),$ then the equation will be as follows.

$$\begin{bmatrix} g_1\\ g_2\\ g_3\\ \dots\\ g_K \end{bmatrix}= \begin{bmatrix} a_{11} & a_{12} & \dots & a_{1N} \\ a_{21} & a_{22} & \dots & a_{2N} \\ a_{31} & a_{32} & \dots & a_{3N} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ a_{K1} & a_{K2} & \dots & a_{KN} \\ \end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix} m_1\\ m_2\\ m_3\\ \dots\\ m_N \end{bmatrix}. \tag{4}$$

In matrix form, the equation above can be expressed as

$$\mathbf{g} = \mathbf{A}\mathbf{m} \tag{5}$$

assuming ($\mathbf{A}$ is NOT necessarily square and can be sparse, too)

$$\mathbf{A}=\begin{bmatrix} a_{11} & a_{12} & \dots & a_{1N} \\ a_{21} & a_{22} & \dots & a_{2N} \\ a_{31} & a_{32} & \dots & a_{3N} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ a_{K1} & a_{K2} & \dots & a_{KN} \\ \end{bmatrix} \tag{6}$$

and each $a_{ij} = \left\{a_{11}, a_{12}, \dots, a_{1N}, a_{21}, a_{22}, \dots, a_{KN} \right\}$ in $\mathbf{A}$ equals

$$a_{ij} = \frac{K\times\left(z_{i}-h\right)}{\left\{\left(x_{i}-\alpha_{j}\right)^{2} + \left(y_{i}-\beta_{j}\right)^{2} + \left(z_{i}-h\right)^{2}\right\}^{3/2}}. \tag{7}$$

The Equivalent Surface Elevation, eq_surface_elev¶

Dampney (1969) gives a condition where the flat equivalent mass surface can be set under the gravity surveying level. In ground surveys, the condition put out by Dampney (1969) also means the range where the flat equivalent mass surface can be laid under the topography. The conditions described below is tied to the average gravity data spacing $\Delta x$.

$$2.5\Delta x<\left(z_{i}-h\right)<6\Delta x. \tag{8}$$

The original Dampney (1969) formulation puts $\left(h - z_{i}\right)$, because in his coordinate system, the level of equivalent layer is numerically larger/more positive than the topography.

We all understand that topographic surface is uneven. Then, Dampney (1969) gives this condition implicitly:

The flat equivalent mass surface should lie at any depth between $\mathrm{min}\left(z\right)-2.5\Delta x$ and $\mathrm{max}\left(z\right)-6\Delta x$ (see Figure 1 below).

The supportfuncs.Dampney_A function above will increase the multiplication factor (the "6" in the "$6\Delta x$") of the $\mathrm{max}\left(z\right)-6\Delta x$ by 0.5 value increments if it finds that $\mathrm{max}\left(z\right)-6\Delta x\geq\mathrm{min}\left(z\right)-2.5\Delta x,$ i.e., it will try with (see the bolded number) $$\mathrm{max}\left(z\right)-\mathbf{6.5}\Delta x,$$ then $$\mathrm{max}\left(z\right)-\mathbf{7.0}\Delta x,$$ then $$\mathrm{max}\left(z\right)-\mathbf{7.5}\Delta x, \dots$$ until the condition of $\mathrm{max}\left(z\right)-\mathbf{b}\Delta x<\mathrm{min}\left(z\right)-2.5\Delta x$ is met, $\mathbf{b}$ being the multiplication factor being increased.

Figure 1. Grey area marks the range of equivalent mass surface/layer level under the topography as suggested in Dampney (1969), red line is midway between the upper and lower bound of that range. The eq_depth_range=[upperBound, lowerBound] array gives out the bounds obeyed by this notebook. This notebook's default gravity data gridding level (using the masses at the equivalent surface/level) is marked by the brown line.

By default, the supportfuncs.Dampney_A function will put the equivalent mass surface (or layer) halfway between the upper and lower bounds of the flat equivalent mass surface/layer's depth range (see the red line in Figure 1). However, users can define their own preferred depth range by passing a value to the eq_surface_elev argument in the supportfuncs.Dampney_A function {e.g., if you want an equivalent layer at -3 km below the mean sea level (the vertical datum depends on the vertical datum of your gravity data and may be different!) then you write supportfuncs.Dampney_A(grav_data_loc, eq_surface_elev=-3000) in your notebook or other development tools (Spyder, VSCode, or others).

Searching for Suitable Mass Array $\mathbf{m}$¶

To this aim, we want to minimise the $\ell^2$-norm $\left|\mathbf{A}\mathbf{m}-\mathbf{g} \right|_2$. However, $\mathbf{g}$ contains negative values, which may result in some negative values in $\mathbf{m}$, too. While this will be fine in MATLAB, I found it problematic in Python because the presence of negative masses in $\mathbf{m}$ makes the modelled gravity values extremely sensitive to the gravity anomaly gridding level. To ensure $\mathbf{g}$ (and $\mathbf{m}$) contains only zeroes and positive values, I first shifted the gravity data by subtracting the minimum gravity anomaly value from them.

grav_data_anom_nonNeg = (grav_data_anom-grav_data_anom.min())

$$\mathbf{g}_{\;(nonNeg)} = \mathbf{g}-\mathrm{min}\left(\mathbf{g}\right). \tag{9}$$

Then, I use scipy.optimize.nnls to minimise the $\left|\mathbf{A}\mathbf{m}-\mathbf{g}_{\;(nonNeg)} \right|_2$ without negative masses in $\mathbf{m}$. The resulting mass, when plugged back into the minimised equation, gives an RMSE of 4.4 mGal, good enough for progressing further! The relationship between the RMSE and the $\ell^2$-norm is as follows.

$$\mathrm{RMSE\;(data\;unit)} = \sqrt{\frac{1}{K}\sum_{i=0}^{K}{\left\{\sum_{j=0}^{N}{\left(a_{ij}m_{j}\right)}-g_{i\;(nonNeg)}\right\}^2}} = \frac{\left | \mathbf{Am}-\mathbf{g}_{\;(nonNeg)}\right |_2}{\sqrt{K}}. \tag{10}$$

RMSE equals the $\ell^2$-norm divided by square root of $K$, the number of gravity data. Meanwhile, $N$ is the number of masses involved in the calculation above.

In [7]:
# Suppose A is your (2000×8000) 2D array, grav is your length-2000 vector.
# Make sure both are NumPy arrays of dtype float64 (or float32).
grav_data_anom_nonNeg = (grav_data_anom-grav_data_anom.min())
mass_nnls, rnorm = nnls(dampney69_A_matrix, grav_data_anom_nonNeg)
#  • mass_nnls is a length-8000 array with all entries ≥ 0
#  • rnorm is the 2‐norm of the residual (‖A·mass_nnls − grav‖₂)

print("First 10 entries of mass:", mass_nnls[:10])
print("Residual norm |A·mass − grav|₂:", rnorm, " mGal")
print("RMSE |A·mass − grav|₂/√(len(grav)):", rnorm/np.sqrt(len(grav_data_anom_nonNeg)), " mGal")

Regridding the Gravity Anomaly at A Flat Surface Above the Topography¶

Once we have the non-negative masses array $\mathbf{m}$ ready, we can recalculate the gravity anomaly at any flat level above the topography. Gauss' law states that outside the source mass, gravity anomaly satisfies the Laplace's equation $\nabla^{2}\Phi=0$, with $\Phi$ as the gravity potential. The Laplace's equation is prerequisite for the applicability of gridding to interpolate gravity anomaly data, and by extension, this formula prohibits gridding inside the topography. Hence, the flat surface for gridding our gravity data should be at least touching/tangential to the topography or above.

The supportfuncs.grav_at_planar_surf function below by default puts the gridding surface 100 m above the highest data point in the survey area ($\approx$ highest topography in some cases, see Figure 1 above). However, users can set the elevation of the gridding surface by setting the height_from_max_data_elev, e.g. if they want to grid it at 2000 m above the highest data elevation, they can write grav_at_planar_surf(grav_data_loc, mass_array, grid_mass_centres, eq_surface_elev, height_from_max_data_elev=2000) in their development tools. Gridding resolution, i.e. the length of the sides of the square pixels in this grid, can be set by passing a positive non-zero value into the supportfuncs.grav_at_planar_surf function (e.g., if you want a 1-km = 1000-m grid resolution, you write grav_at_planar_surf(grav_data_loc, mass_array, grid_mass_centres, eq_surface_elev, grid_res=1000) in your development tool). Default grid resolution is as follows.

$$ \mathtt{default\_grid\_res} = 50\times\mathtt{np.round}\left(\frac{\mathtt{average\_gravity\_spacing}}{100}\right). \tag{11}$$

The function supportfuncs.grav_at_planar_surf calculates $a_{ij}$ in the $\mathbf{A}_{\,gridded}$ by setting the $z_{i} =$ maximum data elevation $+$ height_from_max_data_elev for all grid pixel centres (now $i$ stands for the $i$-th gravity grid pixel). Then, the gridded gravity is calculated by

$$\mathbf{g}_{\,gridded}=\mathbf{A}_{\,gridded}\;\mathbf{m}+\mathrm{min}\left(\mathbf{g}\right). \tag{12}$$

The $\mathrm{min}\left(\mathbf{g}\right)$ is brought back in (12) so the $\mathbf{g}_{\,gridded}$ has the same zero-anomaly datum with the original gravity anomaly data $\mathbf{g}$.

In [8]:
gridded_grav_and_its_locs = supportfuncs.grav_at_planar_surf(grav_data_loc, mass_nnls, grid_mass_centres, eq_surface_elev)
gridded_grav_and_its_locs[:,3] = gridded_grav_and_its_locs[:,3]+grav_data_anom.min() # bringing back the non-negative gravity anomaly value to its real datum

Finding the Survey Boundary Using the alphashape¶

Please modify the alpha value in the supportfuncs.compute_alphashape_from_pts function. The value of alpha is a real number. If alpha=0 or less, supportfuncs.compute_alphashape_from_pts will return the convex hull boundary of the gravity data collection. Higher alpha will make the boundary tighter and tighter until no area is left at a very high alpha value. This boundary will be used to filter/mask out the gridded gravity data outside the original data extent/survey boundary.

In [9]:
# Compute the alpha shape
alpha = 1e-4  # Adjust alpha to control concavity (smaller alpha = more concave)
grav_data_forAlphaShape = [tuple(round(x, 2) for x in sublist) for sublist in grav_data_loc[:,:2]]
grav_data_bound = supportfuncs.compute_alphashape_from_pts(grav_data_forAlphaShape, alpha)

    aspect=25,      # Width-to-height ratio (larger value = thinner colorbar)

    label="Gridded Gravity Anomaly (mGal)"

# Clip the contour plot to the alpha shape
if not grav_data_bound.is_empty:
    # Handle both Polygon and MultiPolygon cases
    if isinstance(grav_data_bound, (Polygon, MultiPolygon)):
        # Extract exterior coordinates from the alpha shape
        if isinstance(grav_data_bound, Polygon):
            x, y = grav_data_bound.exterior.xy
            vertices = np.column_stack((x, y))
        else:  # MultiPolygon
            # Use the first polygon or combine as needed; adjust based on your data
            x, y = grav_data_bound.geoms[0].exterior.xy
            vertices = np.column_stack((x, y))
        
        # Create a matplotlib Path from the alpha shape vertices
        clip_path = mpath.Path(vertices)
        
        # FIXED: Use transData instead of get_transform()
        # transData is the correct transform for data coordinates
        transformed_clip_path = mtransforms.TransformedPath(clip_path, ax[1].transData)
        
        # Apply the clip path ONLY to contour-related collections
        # Get the number of collections before plotting the boundary
        n_collections_before_boundary = len(ax[1].collections)
        
        # Apply clipping only to collections that are part of the contour plot
        # (exclude grid lines and other non-contour collections)
        for i, collection in enumerate(ax[1].collections):
            # Only clip collections that were created by the contour plot
            # Grid lines are typically the first collections, contours come after
            if hasattr(collection, 'get_paths') and len(collection.get_paths()) > 0:
                # This is likely a contour collection
                collection.set_clip_path(transformed_clip_path)
        
        # Also clip any QuadMesh objects (filled contours/pcolormesh) but be selective
        from matplotlib.collections import QuadMesh
        from matplotlib.image import AxesImage
        
        for child in ax[1].get_children():
            # Only clip contour-related objects, not spines, grid, etc.
            if isinstance(child, (QuadMesh, AxesImage)):
                try:
                    child.set_clip_path(transformed_clip_path)
                except:
                    pass

# Plot the boundary
for poly in grav_data_bound.geoms:
    x, y = poly.exterior.xy
    ax[1].plot(x, y, 'r-', label='Alpha Shape-made Survey Boundary', zorder=6)
